<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / Mercury comes up with new number
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury One-2-One, the mobile phone company, was yesterday offering
compensation to the hundreds of new subscribers who could not take advantage
of an offer of free calls on Christmas day because its network was
overloaded.
One-2-One, a sister company to Mercury Communications, had promised
customers buying its phones between November 8 and December 24 an unlimited
number of free calls to anywhere in the world on December 25.
The mobile phone operator said that 80 per cent of new customers
successfully made calls. But the level of demand, which surprised the
company, meant that hundreds of subscribers were unable to make calls,
mainly to numbers abroad.
One-2-One is thought to have received more than 500 complaints and was
yesterday dealing with them on a case-by-case basis, offering free call
credits worth up to Pounds 40 to new subscribers shown on its computer to
have been unable to make calls. It calculated that the average value of
calls by new customers on Christmas day was about Pounds 41.
The company said: 'We would not have launched a promotion if we thought we
could not fulfil it. The company's reputation is very important. We did not
anticipate some people spending the amount of time they did on the phones.
Our forecasts were exceeded dramatically by a number of people.'
At least 20 customers spent more than 12 hours on the phone, while another
20 made more than 2,000 calls between them.
In total, 1.5m calls were made on One-2-One on Christmas day, totalling more
than 6.3m call minutes (105,000 hours) - equivalent to 75 per cent of call
traffic in a typical week. Free calls under the promotion accounted for 4.1m
minutes - for which customers would otherwise have paid more than Pounds 2m.
Some 2.3m minutes of international calls were made, 12 times the Sunday
average.
The operator, a joint venture between Mercury Communications' parent Cable &amp;
Wireless and American company US West, insisted that it had remained within
its Pounds 5m budget for the promotion. The number of One-2-One subscribers
is thought to have risen to almost 200,000, from 140,000 at the end of
September.
It was unclear yesterday whether One-2-One would face regulatory action over
the promotion.
Oftel, the telecommunications watchdog, said Mercury had not breached any of
the conditions of its licence. However, Oftel would take up any complaints
it received about the promotion with One-2-One. It had received two by
yesterday.
Mr Andrew MacKinlay, Labour MP for Thurrock, said this week he was writing
to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, to complain about the
promotion.
</TEXT>
