<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / Life sector is set data standard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Life insurance companies will have to provide information on a standard
basis about how many people buying long-term policies give them up early,
according to rules published yesterday by their regulator.
The move will mean figures will be collected across the financial services
sector in a common format for the first time, enabling comparisons to be
made between different companies and different methods of selling. The first
statistics from this exercise are likely to be out in the autumn.
If investors surrender policies in the first few years, it does not
necessarily mean that they were badly advised. But there would be questions
about whether suitable advice was being provided if many of a company's
customers gave up long-term investments soon after buying them.
The Personal Investment Authority (PIA), the watchdog to protect the private
investor, has so far stopped short of insisting that figures for individual
companies be published, but it is now moving in that direction, in the teeth
of opposition from some companies.
Next year it will consult member companies on requiring life offices to make
their statistics publicly available. In the meantime, it will encourage them
to do so.
Until now there has been no authoritative basis for calculating lapse rates,
which has made it easier for life companies to avoid being put on the spot.
Anecdotal evidence suggests that lapse rates reached their highest levels in
the early 1990s but are coming down slightly as companies develop more
flexible products.
Even so, life companies still sound apprehensive about a report expected
next month from the Office of Fair Trading on endowment policies which will
highlight both lapse rates and the poor values that some companies provide
to people who surrender a policy prematurely.
By the end of June this year, life companies will have to provide the PIA
with lapse rates broken down by five types of life and pensions policies and
by four methods of selling, such as through a sales force or through
independent advisers. From 1996 onwards, the returns will have to be
provided by the end of April.
The PIA's move comes against a background of regulatory pressure for greater
openness in retail financial services. From the beginning of next year,
sales agents and independent advisers will have to give customers more
information about the policies they sell, their charges, and the commission
earned on the sale.
</TEXT>
