FT  30 DEC 94 / US leading indicators ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US official index of leading indicators rose 0.3 per cent last month,
providing further evidence that economic growth is likely to remain robust
in the first half of 1995. The increase in the index, intended to give early
warning of changes in economic trends, exceeded most analysts' expectations.
It followed a revised 0.1 per cent decline in October and a gain of 0.1 per
cent in September. Officials said the index had been boosted by positive
contributions from indicators including orders for plant, equipment, orders
for consumer goods and materials, claims for unemployment insurance, and
commodity prices. Other indicators, including share prices and money supply,
contributed negatively.
