FT  30 DEC 94 / Thai, Malaysian ratings boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Standard &amp; Poors, the rating agency, has raised its credit ratings for
Thailand and Malaysia's long-term foreign-currency debt. Malaysia's rating
was raised to single-A-plus from single-A while Thailand's rating was raised
to single-A from single-A-minus, with a stable long-term outlook for both.
Malaysia's upgrading reflects the country's steady progress in diversifying
its export-based economy, prudent macroeconomic management and a political
system that balances the demands of its multi-ethnic society, the agency
said. Thailand's upgrading reflects the maintenance of the country's
external payments position and the consolidation of civilian-led democratic
rule since 1992.
