<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / Macho managers are bad for health, say guidelines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WOLFFE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employers should renounce the macho management style of the 1980s and
attempt to understand their employees' feelings, according to official
guidelines to be published early in the new year.
The Health and Safety Executive says many employers need to pay more
attention to their relationships with employees to prevent stress-related
ailments in the workplace.
The guidance is the first official health and safety advice to deal with
occupational stress.
'In the 1980s in this country, many employers shared the unfortunate
attitude that admitting to stress was admitting to a personal weakness,'
says the HSE.
'But we all have a threshold - even the tough guys have a threshold which,
when crossed, can become a negative factor. We want to promote the
preventive approach through education.
'There are certain features in the workplace that can aggravate stress, such
as noise and bad lighting. But a very important feature is having good
communications and a sympathetic approach.'
About 80m working days are lost every year because of stress, according to
Department of Health figures published at the Confederation of British
Industry conference last month. Mental health troubles, such as headaches,
irritability and indecision, are estimated to cost the UK economy Pounds
3.7bn annually.
The HSE guidance, mainly aimed at small to medium-sized businesses, comes
after a former social worker last month successfully sued his employer for
negligence over his heavy workload.
Mr John Walker was the first person in the UK to win an action against his
employers after his workload drove him to a nervous breakdown. Mr Walker is
now seeking Pounds 200,000 damages from Northumberland County Council.
Stress at work has risen alongside the fear of redundancy, according to a
survey of 426 private and public sector companies. Research by the
white-collar union MSF, published last week, showed that 43 per cent of
employees feel poorly treated by their employers.
The Institute of Personnel and Development recommends that managers develop
an occupational health strategy to deal with stress. In a study to be
published in February, the IPD advises employers to monitor stress levels
and counsel employees to cope with their work-load.
Mr Doug Gummery, policy adviser, said: 'Stress is a symptom of either a very
unhealthy organisation or a healthy one going through a period of rapid
change or growth, which must be managed properly if the organisation is
going to come through.'
Stress case sends shock through employers' systems, Page 6
</TEXT>
