<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 94 / Mexican finance minister quits as part of rescue plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TED BARDACKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo announced yesterday that as part of an
'emergency economic plan' to be implemented in January he had accepted the
resignation of Mr Jaime Serra Puche as finance minister.
Mr Serra will be replaced by Mr Guillermo Ortiz Martinez, minister of
communications and transport and former chief deputy to Mr Pedro Aspe at the
finance ministry during the presidency of Mr Carlos Salinas.
The emergency plan will seek to mitigate the negative effects on the economy
caused by the 29 per cent devaluation of the peso over the past two weeks
and the resulting financial crisis threatening the country.
In Washington, meanwhile, President Bill Clinton said he backed reform
efforts in Mexico and was looking into 'what we can do' to stabilise the
peso: 'It is something that I take seriously . . . We're talking to the
Mexican government about what we can do.'
Earlier in the day, the Mexican peso stabilised as investors were reassured
by reports that an emergency economic plan would receive backing from
leading industrial countries and international financial institutions.
Mexican reports suggested that the international backing might range from
approval from the Group of Seven leading industrial nations of Mr Zedillo's
proposals to funding of up to Dollars 10bn to ease fears over repayment
obligations.
A delegation from the International Monetary Fund arrived in Mexico City
late on Wednesday night and was reported to have met Mr Zedillo and Mr
Serra, who had been criticised for poor handling of the peso crisis.
In a speech long on explanations of why the devaluation was necessary and
short on details of what concrete economic measures will be taken next year,
Mr Zedillo said last night the new economic plan would include four main
elements: an accord between labour and business that 'prevents falling into
a race between devaluation and inflation'; a fiscal adjustment that would
reduce the country's dangerous current account deficit and imply an
important reduction in government spending; a series of measures to deepen
Mexico's structural reform and international competitiveness, including
further private participation in infrastructure development and ownership;
and the establishment of an international assistance fund 'large enough to
permit financial stability in the shortest time possible'.
At the close, the rate for the peso was 4.875 to the US dollar, slightly up
from Wednesday's close of 4.975, while the Mexican stock market was up 3.14
per cent. Mexican equities in New York continued a slow climb that began on
Wednesday.
Bid to win confidence, Page 5
</TEXT>
