<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow retreats as year-end
rally falters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Stocks retreated from the gains of the past four sessions yesterday as Wall
Street's year-end rally stumbled, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 22.20 at 3,839.49.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 1.61 at 460.86, the
American Stock Exchange composite gained 0.25 to 429.62 and the Nasdaq
composite fell 3.73 to 742.46.
Trading volume on the NYSE came to 244m shares.
Analysts attributed yesterday's losses to profit-taking, but said movements
were exaggerated by the day's low volumes. Many were optimistic that the
late-blooming year-end rally, begun late last week, would continue through
the end of the year.
Upjohn shares closed down Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 30 1/8 after the company
announced it was stopping trials of a drug for head injuries after the
pharmaceuticals company found a higher death rate among trial participants
taking the medication. The announcement fuelled rumours that Upjohn might be
the subject of a takeover bid.
Toys R Us, down Dollars 3 1/8 at Dollars 30 1/8 , declined to discuss its
Christmas sales or comment on a lowering of the 1994 earnings estimate by a
US broker. The plan announced on Tuesday by Home Holdings to cease
underwriting and transfer some business to Zurich Insurance Group of
Switzerland, left the shares down Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 9 7/8 .
Mexican and other Latin American ADRs, which had been depressed in the wake
of Mexico's currency crisis, bounced back as officials from that country
discussed the possibility that the US and Canada would extend a credit
facility to their southern neighbour. Telmex was up Dollars 3 3/4 at Dollars
41 1/2 , Vitro rose Dollars 2 to Dollars 13 3/8 , Compania Telefonos de
Chile rose Dollars 2 3/8 at Dollars 80 and Telefonica de Argentina gained
Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 50 7/8 .
Canada
Surging gold stocks masked a day of broadly-based losses for most stock
groups on the Toronto Stock Exchange today.
After a sharp rise at the opening that breached the 4200 mark, the TSE-300
drifted downward for most of the session, ending the day with a slight gain
in light trading.
The composite index added 8.32 points, or 0.20%, to 4201.52 with advances
over declines 359 to 312.
The gold group added a remarkable 5.22% as the New York spot price for gold
added 2 US dollars to USDollars 383.75.
