FT  29 DEC 94 / International Capital Markets: Credit Lyonnais chief sees
return to black in 1995
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Credit Lyonnais, the state-owned French bank, will make a profit in 1995
after heavy losses in 1993 and 1994, chairman Mr Jean Peyrelevade told
Europe 1 radio, writes John Ridding in Paris.
'The 1995 year will be better than 1994. Finally, we will manage to have
positive results,' he said, without giving details. The state-owned bank has
been implementing a significant restructuring programme aimed at curbing
losses which totalled FFr6.9bn (Dollars 1.27bn) last year. The programme has
included the sale of assets, including FNAC, the music and retail chain, and
a stake in one of France's mobile telephone operators.
Earlier this week, Credit Lyonnais announced that it had sold a 20 per cent
stake in Adidas, the German sports equipment company, for an undisclosed
sum. Prior to this sale, the bank said it had received almost FFr10bn from
asset sales, about half of the target it set for 1994 and 1995.
Credit Lyonnais is one of 21 companies slated for privatisation by the
centre-right government of prime minister Mr Edouard Balladur. Industry
observers say that a return to profit is a condition for privatisation, but
that the government may move quickly to implement a sale once the bank has
returned to the black and strengthened its balance sheet.
