<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / Bank rate likely to be unchanged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, the governor of the
Bank of England, reviewed monetary policy yesterday amid expectations that
they would leave interest rates unchanged at least until their next meeting
on February 2.
As usual, neither the Treasury nor the Bank would reveal the conclusion of
the hour-long talks, which were brought forward from early January because
Mr Clarke leaves this week for a 12-day trade promotion tour in Malaysia,
Thailand and Vietnam.
However, speaking after the meeting, Mr Anthony Nelson, Treasury minister,
made clear that there would be no change in the thrust of policy in spite of
weak consumer confidence.
He told BBC radio's The World at One that the government would continue to
set interest rates to maintain the momentum of recovery while bearing down
on inflation.
Analysts said they did not expect any decision to raise rates would emerge
because the last meeting, when the chancellor increased base rates by 0.5
percentage points to 6.25 per cent on Mr George's recommendation, was only
on December 7.
Although the City believes rates must rise further to curb inflationary
pressures, there has been little economic news since then.
Yesterday's discussions finished before publication of yesterday's report
from the Confederation of British Industry pointing to a rise in pay
settlements.
The talks also came too soon to evaluate retail trends before and after
Christmas.
The minutes of the November monetary meeting, released last week, showed the
chancellor expressing some concern about the effect that tax rises announced
before last month's Budget might have on consumer demand.
Mr Nelson predicted that the government's unpopular decisions of reducing
public expenditure and increasing taxes would yield political as well as
economic dividends.
The minister forecast that personal disposable income would increase next
year in spite of tax increases and that there would be 'further progress'
both for government finances and those of the British people.
However, the Treasury's monthly monetary report for January said 'continuing
steady growth' in the economy was 'concentrated in the company sector'.
Bad feeling, Page 8
</TEXT>
