<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / C&amp;G warns members not to snub Lloyds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society is to issue a blunt statement
telling its members that if they do not approve the Pounds 1.8bn cash offer
from Lloyds Bank, the board intends C&amp;G to remain a building society.
The statement will dismay those C&amp;G members who believe the society could
command a higher price or should become a public limited company on its own.
But it is likely to increase the prospect that any member who wants a share
of the cash incentives will vote for this deal, instead of holding out for
the possibility of a larger handout from a new offer.
The Pounds 1.8bn offered by Lloyds is to be shared mainly among investing
members of more than two years' standing, and depositors. C&amp;G estimates that
the average total payment to an individual will be about Pounds 2,000.
If C&amp;G remains a society, there will be no distribution of cash to members.
The warning that only the Lloyds bid will be put to members and that the
board does not mean to give them a chance to consider other options is
contained in the draft transfer document.
It is due to be sent to all 1m-plus C&amp;G members late in February before they
vote on the plans at a special general meeting on March 31. The move must be
approved by two separate resolutions, from borrowers and investors.
A simple majority of borrowers taking part in the vote is enough to pass
their resolution, but the investors' resolution must be passed by both 75
per cent of those voting and 50 per cent of those eligible to vote.
Before the deal was announced in April, Lloyds agreed with C&amp;G that the
board would not put any other offer to its members for an undisclosed length
of time to preclude a rival bid.
Under building society legislation, a society's board does not have to give
members the opportunity to vote on a proposed offer or takeover bid unless
it wants to.
By far the most likely prospect is that the Lloyds deal will go ahead.
However, even the faintest suggestion that if it does not C&amp;G will stay as a
society is likely to surprise senior executives in other societies.
Many of them regard takeover by a bank as the logical conclusion to C&amp;G's
strategy of concentrating on being a low-cost provider of mortgages and
savings accounts, instead of diversifying into a broader range of personal
financial services as other societies have done.
</TEXT>
