<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / Tec chairman's contracts defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The awarding of contracts by a training and enterprise council to a company
owned by one of its board members was defended yesterday by the Tec National
Council.
Essex Training and Enterprise Council awarded a contract to a business owned
by Mr Roy Lawrence without going through competitive tendering, it emerged
yesterday.
Mr Lawrence, former chairman of Essex Tec, said that in 1991 Mr Philip
Howard, then chief executive, appointed Raytel Insurance Brokers - a company
Mr Lawrence then owned - to arrange insurance cover and pensions without
accepting formal bids from other brokers.
Mr Howard said that when the Tec could not find a 'suitable broker' for its
insurance cover, Mr Lawrence 'offered the help of his broker manager'. The
Tec decided to place its business with Raytel after talking to a few other
brokers because 'the deal was by far the best'.
Mr Lawrence said he did not take part in the decision and fully declared his
interests.
The Department of Employment, which provides about Pounds 2bn in funding to
the 82 employer-led Tecs, which administer government-funded training in
England and Wales, requires all contracts to be awarded impartially. In an
audit of Essex Tec's bidding procedures last year, it said it found 'no
reason to think any impropriety has occurred'.
Mr Howard said that in late 1991 Mr Albert Gable, then head of finance,
asked Raytel to arrange personal pensions for some staff members, again
without putting the contract out to tender.
Mr Gable left the Tec in late 1993, and yesterday refused to comment on the
arrangements.
In May 1993 Mr Michael Clegg took over as chief executive and reviewed the
Tec's pension scheme. A number of brokers were invited to bid for the
account, and Mr Clegg chose to transfer all 30 plans which were placed with
Raytel to the Tec National Pension Scheme.
Mr Chris Humphries, director of policy and strategy at the Tec National
Council, said: 'The whole point of a Tec is that it is based in a community
and requires you to have local people on your board.'
</TEXT>
