<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / 'Shift towards Asia' for steel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A shift in the global pattern of steel production and consumption
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
towards Asia and away from central and eastern Europe - is forecast this
week for the remainder of the 1990s.
By the end of the decade, Asian countries will be consuming nearly 47 per
cent of the world's steel, compared with 34 per cent in 1990, according to a
study by Meps (Europe), the Sheffield steel consultancy.
Over the same period, Asian production will have climbed from 31 per cent of
the global total to nearly 40 per cent, it predicts.
The forecast underlines the importance to the world steel industry of Asian
markets, buoyed by increasing domestic demand because of strong economic
growth rates.
Production of steel in Asia is forecast to rise by 50m tonnes, or 19 per
cent, to 316m tonnes between 1994 and 2000. China will account for the
biggest share of the increase: its output is forecast to rise by 22.5m
tonnes to 113m. The extra production will probably meet the higher demand
for steel in China, says Meps, but it will remain a net importer of steel
well into the next century.
Production in South Korea will continue increasing, reaching 41.5m tonnes by
2000, while Indian steel production is also forecast to grow in the second
half of the 1990s. New capacity is coming on stream in India and more is
likely to be installed.
Meanwhile, the Asean countries will all increase their production to meet at
least part of the higher steel demand. New manufacturing plants for
engineering products will create a strong demand for steel.
Elsewhere, Latin America, South Africa, Iran and Australia will also
increase their share of world production. The main loser, says Meps, will be
the former Soviet Union, as compared with 1990. But even here, growth in
output is expected from 1995, and many east European countries are already
reporting increases in output.
The traditional steelmaking regions - Europe, Japan and the US - will all
have a lower share of total steel production in 2000, says the study.
But the cake will be larger, as the consultancy forecasts a steady increase
in global production from 727.5m tonnes in 1993 to 805m in 2000. It
expresses confidence that 1994 will prove to be the low point in the cycle.
Over the same period, finished steel consumption is expected to rise faster,
from 615.3m to 715m tonnes. Outlook for World Crude Steel Production and
Consumption to 2000. Meps (Europe). Fax UK 0114 2759808. Dollars 425.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XOZ  Asia.
    CNZ  China, Asia.
    KRZ  South Korea, Asia.
    XCZ  Latin America.
    ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
    IRZ  Iran, Middle East.
    AUZ  Australia.
    RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
    XGZ  Europe.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
