<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / Gangsters bag top gun in Thailand's 'bird nest war'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp increase in the price of edible bird's nests prompted a leading
exporter of the 'caviar of the east' to employ a crackshot hired gun who
reportedly killed 14 bird's nest thieves over the past three years.
The gunslinger was himself shot dead as he was leaving a restaurant a week
ago, according to police in Phattalung, southern Thailand.
Mr Tid Musigachinda had been hired by the Laemthong Birds Nest Company to
guard a cave on Koh Si Koh Ha Island where swiftlets build some of the
world's most valuable edible nests.
Conservationists blame the region's economic boom for driving nest hunters
to extremes to satisfy mainly Chinese eaters of what was once an exotic
delicacy for the few.
Traffic International, run by the World Wide Fund for Nature and the World
Conservation Union, reported earlier this year that Hong Kong is easily the
biggest importer of bird's nests, buying 17m swiftlet nests in 1992, the
most recent year for which statistics are available.
In the five years to 1992, the wholesale price of swiftlet nests nearly
trebled to HKDollars 3,586 (Pounds 296) per kilogram; it is said that 1kg of
the finest nests can fetch up to HKDollars 30,000.
Mr Tid was due to stand trial for shooting 14 suspect nest robbers, but
district officials in Phattalung claimed his death makes it much harder to
tackle the bird's nest gangs in Southern Thailand.
'He was the only witness. He was the only one who really knew what was going
on,' said Mr Somphon Nunoon, a provincial councillor. There were rumours
that Bt50,000 (Pounds 1,280) had been offered to anyone who killed the
40-year-old security guard.
Even legal pickers find it difficult to harvest the nests which are built
mainly in limestone caves in Thailand, Indonesia, Vietnam and Malaysia.
The small cup-shaped nests harden like cement after the birds make them from
salivary secretions, but they are eaten in soup or with bamboo pith as a
rare delicacy and a health tonic.
Traffic International blamed a steep decline in the swiftlet population on
the almost continuous harvesting of nests in many areas, which destroys eggs
and chicks.
According to the fund's Mr David Melville, the birds were caught in a
vicious circle: 'Higher prices will lead to yet more intense harvesting and
reduced breeding productivity, leading to higher prices.'
Swiftlet nests would be a sustainable resource only if harvesting took place
before eggs were laid, followed by a closed season of 130 days to allow the
birds to rebuild nests and rear their young.
But Mr Kluem Poolsung, deputy president of Phattalung provincial council,
said: 'Too many people want to make too much money out of too few nests.
Tid's murder will not be the last killing.'
</TEXT>
