FT  29 DEC 94 / Rose in Bihac peace mission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Sir Michael Rose, the UN commander in Bosnia, was reported yesterday
to have won a verbal promise of a truce in Bihac from Mr Fikret Abdic,
renegade Moslem leader, whose troops have fought alongside the Serbs in the
northwestern Moslem enclave. He had talks with both Mr Abdic and General
Atif Dudakovic, commander of the Bosnian government Fifth Corps, in an
attempt to halt fighting which threatens the country's latest ceasefire. A
UN source said Mr Abdic had accepted a three paragraph truce proposed by Gen
Rose. However, Gen Dudakovic is understood to have expressed some
reservations and to have indicated that he would have to consult his
government in Sarajevo. Details of the truce proposal were not immediately
known.
Gen Rose, who until yesterday was prevented by Serb forces from visiting
Bihac, met for talks on implementing a truce in the region, encircled by
Serb forces. Clashes in the Bihac region have thwarted negotiations on the
details of a four-month cessation of hostilities, brokered by Mr Jimmy
Carter, former US president, due to come into force on Sunday. As Gen Rose
held talks in Bihac, fighting flared in the north of the enclave around Mr
Abdic's stronghold of Velika Kladusa, with some 87 shells falling near the
town, according to a UN spokesman in Zagreb.
