FT  29 DEC 94 / Rabin seeks to defuse land row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SILVER and SHAHIRA IDRISS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM, CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israeli prime minister, was last night seeking a way to
climb down from the crisis generated by ground-clearing for a West Bank
settler suburb on land claimed by Palestinian farmers. Mr Yassir Arafat
summoned an emergency meeting of his Palestinian National Authority in Gaza
last night to consider the issue. A spokesman for the PLO chairman demanded
that Israel return the land to the villagers of Khader, south of Bethlehem.
He warned that failure to do so might 'negatively affect' the peace
negotiations. Earlier yesterday Mr Rabin asked Mr Michael Ben-Yair, attorney
general, to clarify the legal situation. Bulldozers, meanwhile, are
continuing to clear the hillside one mile from the settler township of
Efrat. Hundreds of Palestinians mounted a protest vigil there yesterday and
a large Israeli force still guards the site.
Meanwhile, King Fahd of Saudi Arabia arrived unexpectedly in Alexandria
yesterday for a meeting with Presidents Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Hafez
al-Assad of Syria. There was speculation in Egypt that Mr Assad had sought
the meeting to express his concern about the pace at which Israel was
establishing relations with Arab countries, particularly in the Gulf, while
still occupying large areas of Arab territory.
