<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / Major renews tax cut promise: PM admits that rift over
Europe is threatening to destroy the Tory party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major last night made his strongest promise yet to reduce income
tax. He told senior Tory officials it was no longer a question of whether
the government would cut tax, but of when.
In a pugnacious new year's message, delivered with the Conservative party
trailing far behind Labour in successive opinion polls, the prime minister
called for an end to the party's civil war over Europe.
'United the Conservative party can continue to be invincible,' he said. But
he admitted the rift over Europe threatened 'to destroy our party from
within'.
His words, in a letter to Tory constituency chairmen, cut little ice either
with Labour or with Conservative Eurosceptics. Mr John Prescott, Labour
deputy leader, said Mr Major had 'confirmed his desperation over Europe and
his unbelievable complacency over everything else'.
Sir Teddy Taylor, the Euro-sceptic MP for Southend East who was among those
suspended from the parliamentary party for not supporting the government in
a confidence vote on Europe last month, said Mr Major could unite the party
if he would 'identify the real issues in Europe and take a strongly
Eurosceptic line on them'.
In comments made a week after new Treasury figures confirmed that the amount
of tax the government takes from the average family was set to rise again
next year, Mr Major said the day ministers could revert to their
'tax-cutting agenda' was getting closer.
Reaffirming the government's pledge to 'make progress towards' a 20p basic
income tax rate as soon as prudently possible, he argued that the
Conservatives were still 'the only party committed to low taxation'.
But amid indications that the so-called 'feel bad' factor among consumers
may be spreading to business, he appeared to acknowledge that the benefits
of Britain's improving economy were not yet getting through to voters.
'People have been through the pain and not yet seen the gain,' he said. 'But
the pain was necessary to create the present favourable prospects.'
His remarks came after Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, said the
Conservatives had lost credibility as the party of low taxation after
raising taxes by the equivalent of 7p on the standard rate of income tax.
The government would 'insult the intelligence of the British electorate' if
it expected people to be grateful for getting some of that money back, said
Mr Blair, who will deliver his own new year's message today.
He said tax cuts should not become 'just another political ploy by the
Conservatives to retain power'.
On Europe, Mr Major sought to portray himself as a mediator between the
warring Eurosceptic and pro-European extremes in the Conservative party,
saying he agreed with those who thought Brussels interfered too much in
'day-to-day affairs'. But he said the government had 'won the argument' to
ensure that Europe intervened as little as possible in people's everyday
lives.
In an uncompromising call for Tory rebels to train their fire on 'our real
opponents', he said that nothing was more soul-destroying for the party's
grass roots supporters than 'to see those whom they helped to get elected
arguing against other Conservatives'.
Bank rate likely to be unchanged, Page 4
Bad feeling about a good recovery, Page 8
</TEXT>
