<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 94 / Mexican markets rebound as IMF crisis talks begin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TED BARDACKE, STEPHEN FIDLER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Mexican stock market and currency rebounded yesterday as talks got under
way between the government and the International Monetary Fund and other
financing agencies which could lead to an emergency financial package.
Mexican officials held urgent meetings in Washington to try to negotiate the
support package.
A US Treasury official said last night that Mexico had not drawn on nearly
Dollars 7bn (Pounds 4.46bn) in currency support lines offered by the US and
Canada, but he confirmed that discussions were under way on external support
for Mexico. He refused to provide details.
Also yesterday, doubts were surfacing about Mexico's ability to repay
holders of its dollar-denominated government securities. The government,
which faces a financial crisis following a sharp devaluation of the peso
during the past week, is seeking funds to back a currency stabilisation
plan, which it is expected to announce soon.
The meetings with the IMF and other financing agencies were adjourned
yesterday as an IMF mission headed for Mexico City.
There were unconfirmed reports yesterday of support for the peso by the New
York Federal Reserve. The spot rate for the peso rose to close at 4.975 to
the dollar, compared with 5.6 at Tuesday's close when the currency had
fallen 39 per cent since December 19. Helped by the strengthening peso, the
Mexican stock market recovered yesterday and was up 2.67 per cent at the
close.
In New York, Mexican shares recovered sharply after Tuesday's falls, with
Telmex up 9.93 per cent at 41 1/2 and Televisa up 7.95 per cent at 32 1/4 .
The doubts about the government's ability to service debt arose after it had
become clear this week that many holders of tesobonos (short-term,
dollar-denominated securities issued by the government) would be unwilling
to buy further securities as their existing paper matured. The central bank
offered Dollars 950m in tesobonos on Tuesday but only Dollars 27.6m was
purchased.
About Dollars 3.5bn in tesobonos will come due in the next five weeks, as
will an additional Dollars 13bn between February and June. Some 80 per cent
of these bonds are held by foreign investors - many by US mutual funds.
If the trend continues, the Mexican government will face further pressure on
its already limited reserves.
Reuter adds from Mexico City: Mexican agrarian reform minister Miguel Limon
pledged yesterday to tackle a main cause of a year-old rebellion in the
southern state of Chiapas by redistributing land from large ranchers to poor
peasants.
