<HEADLINE>
FT  28 DEC 94 / Markets report: Peso slumps to record lows against US dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN the aftermath of the Christmas holiday, the American foreign exchange
markets continued to provide the main focus of market interest, write Lisa
Bransten and Gillian Tett.
The dollar was steady within year-end ranges against major currencies
yesterday while the Mexican peso hit record lows against the US currency.
Late in the session the US currency was mixed against the Japanese yen and
the D-Mark. The dollar rose modestly to Y100.44 up from Y100.18 late Friday,
while falling slightly to DM1.5758 against the German currency from DM1.5790
Friday.
Meanwhile trading in Europe was extremely quiet, with London and several
other major exchanges still closed after the Christmas holiday.
The peso added to last week's dramatic losses yesterday falling about 10 per
cent against the dollar. By late afternoon the same-day, 24-hour and 48-hour
contracts closed 50 centavos down to 5.40/5.60 new pesos to the dollar while
same day contracts fell 1.05 new pesos from Friday's close to 5.55/5.75.
Last week the peso lost 30 per cent against the dollar.
Activity in the peso market was extremely volatile. Many traders were
watching the Mexican stock market for clues about what the peso might do.
The bolsa's key IPC index plunged further in late afternoon trading.
Some traders attributed the peso's continued plunge to growing tension in
the state of Chiapas as the anniversary of the peasant uprising in that
state approaches.
On January 1 of this year a group in Chiapas launched a rebellion against
state authorities that remains unsettled.
Late in the day, the US Treasury department a statement saying that 'recent
movements in the peso have gone far beyond what can be justified by
economics.'
In Washington a World Bank official was quoted by Reuter as saying that
Mexico was unlikely to draw on the Dollars 6bn swap facility arranged
between its central bank and US agencies to calm financial markets. He said
that it could only tap it in the event of a 'real catastrophe', such as the
collapse of oil prices.
Against major currencies, the dollar was trading within recent ranges.
Margaret Kudarauskas, a senior foreign exchange analyst at Thomson Financial
Services, said there was no fundamental reason for the dollar's gain against
the yen.
She added that rumours of orders to sell large amounts of dollars of the
currency runs up between Y100.50 and Y101 would probably keep the US
currency below the Y100.50 mark.
The dollar's loss against the D-Mark came as that currency gained against
other European currencies.
Volume on US currency markets was extremely light with most market activity
due to companies purchasing foreign exchange for business reasons, not
traders betting on rising or falling currency values, according to Ms
Kudarauskas.
The peso continued to be the main focus of the day, as it plunged to a new
low point against the dollar in nervous trading.
Most market activity yesterday - and most of last week - was due to
companies purchasing foreign exchange for business reasons, not traders
betting on rising or falling currency values, according to Ms Kudarauskas.
Trading in Europe was extremely quiet yesterday, with the London exchanges
remaining closed. Sterling weakened slightly against the D-Mark, closing at
DM2.438, down from Friday's close of DM2.441.
Against the American currency it also weakened fractionally, closing at
Dollars 1.546, down from Dollars 1.547 at the close on Friday.
Trading in the European crosses was also extremely quiet, although the lira
slipped slightly against the D-Mark, as the Italian currency continued to be
undermined by the political uncertainty gripping the country.
The Turkish central bank raised its overnight lending rate to 110 per cent
in the afternoon from 95 opening to control dollar rates, bankers said.
