<HEADLINE>
FT  28 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
No apologies for picking an old film tonight. If . . . (10pm Channel 4)
stands head and shoulders above most of the cinematic dross foisted on us
over the past few days. The director Lindsay Anderson once upbraided me for
apologising for my excessive enthusiasm, so let me declare defiantly that
this is simply one of the best British movies ever.
Anderson's 1968 tale of public school revolt is funny, surrealistic, even
romantic.
It has been interpreted at various levels, notably as an attack on the
Establishment, which of course it is; but the director himself pointed out
that it was nothing so crass as a mere hatchet job on public schools - the
thread of nostalgia is deliberate.
However you take it, direction and acting are superb, not just from Malcolm
McDowell's non-conformist schoolboy but a host of stalwart performers like
Peter Jeffrey (a blandly fatuous headmaster), Graham Crowden (a convincingly
dotty history master) and Arthur Lowe's bumbling housemaster, piping
Purcell's 'Fairest Isle' with his wife in the dark watches of the loveless
night.
</TEXT>
