<HEADLINE>
FT  28 DEC 94 / Manual workers 'behind on wages'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The earnings of non-manual employees have risen more than three times as
quickly in the past 15 years as those of workers in manufacturing, say
government figures.
Earnings of full-time non-manual employees in the private sector rose by
56.3 per cent in real terms between 1979 and 1994, Mr Phillip Oppenheim,
employment minister, said in a Commons written answer. This compared with
17.6 per cent for full-time manual workers in manufacturing.
Meanwhile, a Labour MP, Mr Denis McShane, said government figures showed
that one in six blue-collar workers had weekly earnings before deductions of
less than Pounds 150.
