<HEADLINE>
FT  28 DEC 94 / India's ex-President Singh dies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Priests of several religions offered last prayers for former President Zail
Singh, India's first Sikh head of state, as his body was cremated according
to Sikh custom yesterday (pictured above), Reuter reports from New Delhi
Hindu, Moslem, Sikh, Christian and Buddhist prayers were chanted on the
banks of the Yamuna river in Delhi near the memorials to two of India's
founding leaders, Jawaharlal Nehru and Mahatma Gandhi.
Prime Minister P V Narasimha Rao laid a wreath on the body at the ceremony
attended by ministers, opposition leaders and chiefs of the army, navy and
air force.
Singh, who was 78, died in the northern city of Chandigarh on Sunday after
suffering multiple fractures when his car was hit by a truck on November 29.
He was appointed by then-prime minister Indira Gandhi, and served as
president from 1982 to 1987.
He was called Giani, or scholar, for his mastery of Sikh scriptures.
</TEXT>
