<HEADLINE>
FT  28 DEC 94 / Bulgaria's ex-Communists win
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SOFIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bulgarian President Zhelyu Zhelev yesterday urged the Socialist party of
former Communists, the clear winner of the December 18 elections, to form a
government without any ally.
Confirming previously announced unofficial results, Ms Ralitsa Negentsova, a
spokeswoman for the Election Commission, said the Socialists won an absolute
majority of 125 seats in the 240-seat parliament. Their main opponent, the
staunchly anti-Communist Union of Democratic Forces, gained 69 seats.
The Socialists have been seeking a multi-party government, which they say is
necessary to deal with Bulgaria's deeply rooted economic problems.
