<HEADLINE>
FT  28 DEC 94 / US consumer confidence up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US consumer confidence rose nearly two points in December, to 102.2, its
highest level in more than four years, the Conference Board, a New York
business analysis group, reported yesterday.
Confidence varied substantially by region with gains in central and southern
regions offset by modest declines on the east and west coasts.
Separately, the National Association of Realtors reported a 2.6 per cent
decline in sales of existing (as opposed to new) homes between October and
November, to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 3.81m. Sales were 7.5 per
cent down from November last year. Analysts blamed sluggish sales on recent
increases in mortgage rates.
