<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / TV Highlights: Seasonal retrospectives heave into view
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With its hunt meets, sporting fixtures and panto openings, Boxing Day is
traditionally frivolous, as opposed to the spirituality and gravitas we have
so far observed.
Watchable films start at 8.05am (BBC2) with Little Women, 1949 vintage, when
the young Elizabeth Taylor gave signs of becoming a delightful comic
actress.
Good films on all four main channels; my selection would include True Grit
(2.55pm, BBC1), veteran John Wayne and enchanting Kim Darby in the western
with the quaintly formal dialogue (and at least one pentameter worthy of the
Jacobeans: 'He never played me false until he killed me'); Valentino in The
Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (3.25pm, C4); and Bergman and Peck as shrink
and possibly murderous patient in Hitchcock's Spellbound (12.30am, BBC1).
Pride of place goes to the posthumous premiere of the late Dennis Potter's
last completed work, Midnight Movie, a story of obsession and tortuous
longings.
I know Potter is canonised, but will this redeem his latterday tendency to
lugubrious self-indulgence?
And so to post-Boxing Day Tuesday.
BBC2 rather pusillanimously schedules Baa Baa Black Sheep for 3pm. Michael
Berkeley's opera blends an unhappy episode from Rudyard Kipling's childhood
with his later creations from The Jungle Book. Jonathan Moore's original
production for Opera North was highly praised. Barrie Gavin does it for
tele-vision.
Elsewhere seasonal retrospectives heave into view. Films of the Year
(10.50pm, BBC1) is for those who can stand Barry Norman's unremitting
autopilot chirpiness. Video Nation Review of the Year is much more
absorb-ing - all human life is there.
Talking of distinctions, the film alleged to have lost more money in America
than any other arrives on C4 when The Adventures of Baron Munchausen takes
the air - cast including Alison Steadman, Oliver Reed and an un-Faginesque
Jonathan Pryce.
And the originally derided but fascinatingly alive film of Othello, directed
by Orson Welles, surfaces in a restored version (C4, 10.35pm). Welles
himself plays the Moor to Michael MacLiammoir's Iago. Setting Roderigo's
murder in a Turkish bath was necessitated by the shoestring budget and lack
of costumes. Like much else in the film, it works brilliantly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
